Canadian Natural Gas Increases as Low Prices Attract Traders

-- B y   C o l i n   M c C l e l l a n d
-- 
2011-08-17T18:59:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-17/canadian-natural-gas-rises-as-traders-consider-hurricane-season.html
Canadian natural gas rose for the
first time in four days as traders found the power-plant fuel
too cheap to resist while crude oil markets gained.  Gas prices, which usually follow their U.S. counterparts on
the  New York Mercantile Exchange , rose 0.5 percent as Western
 Canada  Select crude added $1.05 to $74.35 a barrel in  New York .  “Natural gas looks like it’s on sale at the current
level,”  James Cordier , portfolio manager at OptionSellers.com
in Tampa, Florida, said in a telephone interview. “Oil is
really on much firmer footing now, the fears in the stock market
we had two weeks ago seem to have abated and natural gas is
going along for the ride.”  Alberta  gas for September delivery gained 1.5 cents to
C$3.38 per gigajoule ($3.26 per million British thermal units)
as of 2:45 p.m. New York time, according to  NGX , a Canadian
Internet market. October gas advanced 2.75 cents to C$3.3925.
Gas traded on the exchange goes to users in Canada and the U.S.
and is priced on  TransCanada Corp. (TRP) ’s Alberta system.  In New York, natural gas for September delivery rose 0.1
cent to settle at $3.933 per million Btu.  Volume on TransCanada’s  Alberta system , which collects the
output of most of the nation’s gas wells, was 15.4 billion cubic
feet as of 1:30 p.m. in New York.  Gas Flows  Gas was flowing at a daily rate of 2.66 billion cubic feet
at Empress, Alberta, where the fuel is transferred to
TransCanada’s main line.  At McNeil, Saskatchewan, where gas is transferred to the
Northern Border Pipeline for shipment to the Chicago area, the
daily flow rate was 1.96 billion cubic feet.  Available capacity on TransCanada’s British Columbia system
at Kingsgate was 1.32 billion cubic feet. The system was
forecast to carry 1.44 billion cubic feet today, about 52
percent of its capacity of 2.58 billion.  Gas at the Alliance Pipeline delivery point near  Chicago 
dropped 2.95 cents, or 0.7 percent, to $4.0741 per million Btu
as of 1:21 p.m. New York time on the Intercontinental Exchange.
Alliance is an express line that can carry 1.5 billion cubic
feet a day to the Midwest from western Canada.  At the Kingsgate point on the border of  Idaho  and British
Columbia, gas fell 0.64 cent, or 0.2 percent, to $3.803.  To contact the reporter on this story:
